 recovery. From their improvised medical treatment in their home countries, to the MSF-run hospital in Amman Jordan, to their return home, Kovacic explores how individuals attempt to pick up the pieces of their previous lives, add new elements from their treatment and travel experiences, and finally establish a new reconstructed reality.The book explores how the interaction between MSF staff and their patients contributes to the immense task of healing that awaits victims of war. The reader visits the intimate medical and domestic spaces that usually remain closed to the outside observer, spaces rich with human contact, perceptions, emotions, conflicts and reconciliations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilian war casualtiesxRehabilitationzMiddle East. 0aPhysician and patientzMiddle East. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh  aIraq war.  aMédecins Sans Frontières.  aSyrian war.  acivilians.  ahumanitarian surgery.  ahumanitarianism.  amedical anthropology.  anon-combatants.  apatient care.  apatient-centered.  areconstructive surgery.  aresilience.  atrauma.  avictims of war.  awar.1 aKovačič, Vanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616159840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526161598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526161598/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles